The Geometry of Severe Malaria

A Vignette

David Smith

2022-05-27

.

We need to develop a model for severe malaria.

  • Introduction

  • The parasite phenotype model assumes severe malaria is a result of exposure to a severe phenotype.

Intro

Severe malaria is the condition that includes most malaria mortality, so it is of great importance to understand the factors that contribute to its incidence. Here, we develop mathematical models severe malaria and its causes and incidence by age in a population, and we explore the geometry of the functional relationships between exposure intensity and incidence by age. We ask two questions:

  • What malarial factors the total incidence of malaria summed over the age of a population?

  • What non-malarial factors affect the incidence of severe malaria?

Phenotype

.

Outline

  • Exposure vs. age

Age

One hypothesis is that severe malaria is caused by exposure to a severe phenotype. One possible way to formulate this model is the following. Suppose that there are \(N\) phenotypes circulating.

wt = function(a){
  s = 1/15/365 
  0.1 + 1.4*s*a/(0.1 + s*a)
}
a=seq(0,3650, length.out=100)
plot(a/365, wt(a), type = "l")

Dynamics

  • Let \(N\) denote the number of severe phenotypes, and we let each phenotype cause a severe case with probability \(T/N\).

    • There are \(T\) total bad phenotypes.

    • In a model with no immune decay and no maternal protection, the total number of cases is at most \(T\).

  • Let \(V\) denote a tracking variable with a decay rate.

    • The probability a phenotype has been seen recently is \(e^{-V/N}\)

  • A parameter Ve modifies whether the model tracks EIR (Ve=1) or FoI (Ve=0).

severeDE = function(a,y,p){with(as.list(c(y,p)),{
  foi = eir2foi(b*eir*wt(a), tau=10) 
  M = M0*exp(-a/Mdk) 
#  dV = (b*eir*Ve + (1-Ve)*foi)*exp(-M) - Vdk*V
  dV = (b*eir*Ve + (1-Ve)*foi) - Vdk*V
  dSevere = T/N*exp(-(V+M)/N)*foi
  list(c(dV, dSevere)) 
})}

severeSolve = function(eir, b=0.55, Ve=0, N=25, Md=10, Mdk=90, Vdk=0, Tot=1, Tmax=3650){
  tms = 0:Tmax
  foi = eir2foi(eir, tau=10) 
  M0 = (b*eir*Ve + (1-Ve)*foi)*7300/Md 
  prms = c(b=b, eir=eir, N=N, Ve=Ve, M0=M0, Mdk=Mdk, Vdk=Vdk, T=Tot) 
  VM = data.frame(lsode(c(V=0,Severe=0), times=tms, severeDE, prms)) 
  return(VM)
} 
severeSolve(1/365) -> out

Plots

.

plotSevere = function(N, Ve=0, Vdk=0, Md=50){
  colors = turbo(6)
  deir = 3^c(0:5)/365
  vmc = list() 
  for(i in 1:6) vmc[[i]]  = severeSolve(deir[i], N=N, Ve=Ve, Vdk=Vdk, Md=Md)
 
  ylm1 = range(diff(vmc[[1]]$Severe))
  for(i in 2:6) ylm1 = range(ylm1, diff(vmc[[i]]$Severe))
    
  ylm2 = range(c(0,1)) 
  for(i in 1:6) ylm2 = range(ylm2, vmc[[i]]$Severe)
   
  with(vmc[[i]], plot(time[-1]/365,  diff(Severe)*365, ylab = "Age (Years)", ylim = ylm1*365, type = "l", col = colors[1], main = paste("N=", N)))
  for(i in 2:6) with(vmc[[i]], lines(time[-1]/365, diff(Severe)*365, col = colors[i]))

  with(vmc[[i]], plot(time/365,  Severe, ylim = ylm2, ylab = "Age (Years)", type = "l", col = colors[1], main = paste("N=",N)))
  for(i in 2:6) with(vmc[[i]], lines(time/365, Severe, col = colors[i]))
}
